    "answers": [
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/dVLIh.jpg?s=256",
                "account_id": 5281408,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 4216641,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/4216641/turing85",
                "reputation": 20275,
                "display_name": "Turing85"
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 4.0",
            "score": 4,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1704642130,
            "creation_date": 1704638133,
            "body": "<p>I would propose two orthogonal refactorings.<\/p>\n<p>First, I propose to replace <code>int code<\/code> with an <code>enum Code<\/code>, so we have values with semantic names.<\/p>\n<p>Second, I propose to use a <code>Map&lt;Code, List&lt;String&gt;&gt;<\/code>, which we can then access with a value of <code>Code<\/code>. If we want only to use this optimization, we can use a <code>Map&lt;Integer, List&lt;String&gt;&gt;<\/code> instead.<\/p>\n<p>Taking this all together, a solution might look like this:<\/p>\n<pre><code>public enum Code {\n  FOO, BAR\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n<hr />\n<pre><code>Map&lt;Code, List&lt;String&gt;&gt; map = ...;\n\nboolean contains(Code code, String stringObject) {\n  return map.getOrDefault(code, List.of()).contains(stringObject);\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n",
            "answer_id": 77773471,
            "question_id": 77773416,
            "last_edit_date": 1704642130
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/zHTaT.png?s=256",
                "account_id": 39208,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 112968,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/112968/knittl",
                "reputation": 269427,
                "display_name": "knittl",
                "accept_rate": 68
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 4.0",
            "score": 2,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1704695593,
            "creation_date": 1704653011,
            "body": "<p>You can extract a method, which selects the list (or collection) on which you want to call <code>contains<\/code>. This can be implemented with a switch/case, an array, or a <code>Map&lt;Integer, List&lt;String&gt;&gt;<\/code>. The fallback is returning an empty collection (which never contains anything, so returns false).<\/p>\n<pre><code>static List&lt;String&gt; listByCode(final int code) {\n  switch (code) {\n    case 1: return ClassName.static_list1;\n    case 2: return ClassName.static_list2;\n    case 3: return ClassName.static_list3;\n    case 4: return ClassName.static_list4;\n    default: return Collections.emptyList();\n  }\n}\n\n// call site (your existing code):\nreturn listByCode(code).contains(string_object);\n<\/code><\/pre>\n<p>Alternative solutions using an array:<\/p>\n<pre><code>private static List&lt;String&gt;[] lists = {\n  ClassName.static_list1,\n  ClassName.static_list2,\n  ClassName.static_list3,\n  ClassName.static_list4\n}\n\nstatic List&lt;String&gt; listByCode(final int code) {\n  return code &gt; 0 &amp;&amp; code &lt; lists.length\n      ? lists[code - 1]\n      : Collections.emptyList();\n  // alternatively: don't check and just throw an ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n<p>\u2026 and with a Map:<\/p>\n<pre><code>private static Map&lt;Integer, List&lt;String&gt;&gt; listsByCode = Map.of(\n    1, ClassName.static_list1,\n    2, ClassName.static_list2,\n    3, ClassName.static_list3,\n    4, ClassName.static_list4\n);\n\nstatic List&lt;String&gt; listByCode(final int code) {\n  return listsByCode.getOrDefault(code, Collections.emptyList());\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n<p>Note that the array- and map-based solutions do not allow you to replace the list references in your class, whereas the switch-based solution does. But maybe you don't need to have separate references and the array/map can be the canononical way to access those lists.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 77774377,
            "question_id": 77773416,
            "last_edit_date": 1704695593
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/kKvXH.gif?s=256",
                "account_id": 31180,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 85421,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/85421/user85421",
                "reputation": 29752,
                "display_name": "user85421"
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 4.0",
            "score": 2,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1704699150,
            "creation_date": 1704660922,
            "body": "<h1>Switch expressions<\/h1>\n<p>Using <a href=\"https://openjdk.org/jeps/361\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">switch expression<\/a>, available since Java 14:<\/p>\n<pre class=\"lang-java prettyprint-override\"><code>return switch (code) {\n    case 1 -&gt; ClassName.staticList1.contains(stringObject);\n    case 2 -&gt; ClassName.staticList2.contains(stringObject);\n    case 3 -&gt; ClassName.staticList3.contains(stringObject);\n    case 4 -&gt; ClassName.staticList4.contains(stringObject);\n    default -&gt; false;\n};\n<\/code><\/pre>\n<p>The call to <code>contains()<\/code> can be factored out of the switch, but not sure if that is worth it (adding an empty dummy list for the <code>default<\/code> case, maybe less <em>clean<\/em>.)<\/p>\n<p>BTW Java Naming convention <code>string_object<\/code>-&gt;<code>stringObject<\/code>, <code>static_list1<\/code>-&gt;<code>staticList1<\/code>, ...<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 77774838,
            "question_id": 77773416,
            "community_owned_date": 1704660922,
            "last_edit_date": 1704699150
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/a/AAcHTteMQd7SEc1EOfu043M1Yb5eEe48W29t0ODPvOHivlbV=k-s256",
                "account_id": 29055001,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 22256940,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/22256940/luigi-dangelo",
                "reputation": 73,
                "display_name": "Luigi D&#39;Angelo"
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 4.0",
            "score": 2,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1705059855,
            "creation_date": 1705059855,
            "body": "<p>this is the best way in my opinion:<\/p>\n<pre><code>static List&lt;String&gt; searchByCode(final int code) {\n  switch (code) {\n    case 1: \n        return ClassName.static_list1;\n    case 2: \n        return ClassName.static_list2;\n    case 3: \n        return ClassName.static_list3;\n    case 4: \n        return ClassName.static_list4;\n    default: \n        return Collections.emptyList();\n  }\n}\n\nreturn searchByCode(code).contains(string_object);\n<\/code><\/pre>\n",
            "answer_id": 77806328,
            "question_id": 77773416
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/a-/AOh14GjBvRwyIejjxGzAoRy2weaI_pwajgwQr5qy3V9J=k-s256",
                "account_id": 17999363,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 13081625,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/13081625/juliean",
                "reputation": 1316,
                "display_name": "Juliean"
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 4.0",
            "score": 0,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1704637591,
            "creation_date": 1704637591,
            "body": "<p>Aside from using a switch-statement (as mentioned), you should also consider making a method that returns just the list, based on the passed in code. Your current code duplicates that &quot;contains(string_object)&quot;-statments onto every branch. The way I would handle this, is the following (pseudo-code):<\/p>\n<pre><code>var list = ClassName.getList(code); // implement static &quot;getList&quot; with a switch-statement\nif (list)\n    return list.contains(string_object);\nelse\n    return false;\n<\/code><\/pre>\n",
            "answer_id": 77773444,
            "question_id": 77773416
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/uAEcW.jpg?s=256",
                "account_id": 1689973,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 1552534,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1552534/wjs",
                "reputation": 40206,
                "display_name": "WJS"
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 4.0",
            "score": -1,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1704642353,
            "creation_date": 1704639242,
            "body": "<p>Try it like this.  Just use a map and put the lists in that.<\/p>\n<pre><code>public class ClassName {\n    static List&lt;String&gt; static_list1 = List.of(&quot;A&quot;, &quot;B&quot;);\n    static List&lt;String&gt; static_list2 = List.of(&quot;C&quot;, &quot;D&quot;);\n    static List&lt;String&gt; static_list3 = List.of(&quot;E&quot;, &quot;F&quot;);\n    static List&lt;String&gt; static_list4 = List.of(&quot;G&quot;, &quot;H&quot;);\n    static Map&lt;Integer, List&lt;String&gt;&gt; map = Map.of(1, ClassName.static_list1, 2,\n            ClassName.static_list2, 3, ClassName.static_list3, 4,\n            ClassName.static_list4);\n\n    public static void main(String[] args) {\n        System.out.println(contains(10,&quot;A&quot;));\n        System.out.println(contains(1,&quot;A&quot;));\n        System.out.println(contains(1,&quot;C&quot;));\n        System.out.println(contains(2,&quot;D&quot;));\n        System.out.println(contains(3,&quot;A&quot;));\n    }\n// Unless the code is in the map and the object is \n// in the list, false will be returned.\n\n    public static boolean contains(int code, String object) {\n        return map.containsKey(code) &amp;&amp; map.get(code).contains(object);\n    }\n\n}\n\n<\/code><\/pre>\n<p>prints<\/p>\n<pre><code>false\ntrue\nfalse\ntrue\nfalse\n\n<\/code><\/pre>\n",
            "answer_id": 77773542,
            "question_id": 77773416,
            "last_edit_date": 1704642353
        }
    ],
